stimulus:
This experiment uses your camera for eye tracking.

No video is saved from this experiment. The only data recorded are predictions about where you are looking.

Before we begin, there are a few things to do that can improve the accuracy of the eye tracking.

If you wear glasses and can complete the task without them, please remove your glasses.

If you need to keep your glasses on to read this text, you can leave them on.

Please close additional browser tabs and apps running in the background.

The eye tracker works best when there are fewer things running at the same time.

Try to avoid bright lights behind you.

The eye tracker works best if your face is well lit from the front.

If you can, adjust the lighting in your room.
Turn off anything that may produce an alert or notification during the task.

In order to participate you must allow the experiment to use your camera.

You will be prompted to do this on the next screen.

If you do not wish to allow use of your camera, you cannot participate in this experiment.

It may take up to 30 seconds for the camera to initialize after you give permission.

Now you'll calibrate the eye tracking, so that the software can use the image of your eyes to predict where you are looking.

You'll see a series of dots appear on the screen. Look at each dot and click on it.

Now we'll measure the accuracy of the calibration.

Keep your head still, and move your eyes to look at the dots.

Please move your mouse to the corner of your screen so it does not distract you

You do not need to click on the dots this time.

Great, we're done with calibration!

Remember to keep your head still as you continue to the experiment.

In this experiment, different scenes will appear in the center of the screen alongside a voice recording that will be played.

If the spoken sentence is applicable to the accompanying scene, press the letter F on the keyboard.

If the scene seems to not be applicable, press the letter J.

Press any key to begin.

Here is trial 1.

Listen to the sentence: is that sentence possible with the image you see on the screen?

F for possible, J for not possible.

Press any key to begin.

Good Job!

There is no fireplace, so it is not possible for the person to light the fire. We will have one more trial.

Press any key to continue

Here is trial 2.

Listen to the sentence: is that sentence possible with the image you see on the screen?

Press any key to begin.

Wrong. There is a postman and the postman can ride the bike!

Now that you understand, we will continue with the experiment. Please remember to keep your head as still as possible

Press any key to continue

You've finished the last task. Thanks for participating!

We have everything we need now, but if you would like to read on and learn more about our study please feel free.

This study is an attempt to replicate Altman & Kamide's 1999 study
"Incremental interpretation at verbs: restricting the domain of subsequent reference."

They were interested, and now we are, to see if verbs that are specific to one object restrict your possible predictions about the end of the sentence.

You just heard a lot of sentences, and sometimes the verbs could apply to one object in the picture or sometimes they applied to all of them.
The eye tracker was trying to see how quickly your eyes jumped to the object the sentence was about-
Before the object was named? After the verb?

We're expecting that your eyes jumped quicker to the target object when the verb was restrictive
(that is, it could reasonably be applied to only one object), than when it wasn't restrictive.
If that is true, it might support the idea that people are predicting what the end of sentences are before they've even heard them.

Please let the experimenter know you have completed the study.
